This is literally why I share my music. …

This is literally why I share my music. 

Received these messages from a woman in California that I've never met or talked to.

Aside from creating it first and foremost for myself and my own therapeutic and cathartic reasons, the greatest thing I could ever ask for, is for what I create to have this kind of impact on people that are going through the depths of suffering and darkest nights of their soul. 

Whatever levels of money, fame, social or streaming numbers or any other forms of "musical success" I may achieve, nothing will ever come close to receiving feedback like this from people.

Music by my favorite artists has literally saved my life and gotten me through the darkest times I've ever experienced. 

To be able to be that for someone else through my music is literally one of the greatest accomplishments of my life and that will never change. 

Keep creating and sharing!! You never know who you might touch and help

Meet the Band:

Lance Kotter (32) is a multi-instrumentalist, composer, and Certified Music Practitioner whose love for music began before he could tie his shoes. Starting guitar at five and later discovering the cello in sixth grade, he immersed himself in advanced orchestras and bands through his school years. By high school, Lance had added drums, bass, multiple guitar styles, and vocals to his repertoire, eventually touring with a band.
In 2011, he found a lifelong companion—the harp—which inspired an original album in 2012. After two years in Poland on an LDS mission, he returned to expand his skills, launching his own project, Co-Create, while busking to fund business college. Today, Lance uses harp therapy to support patients dealing with anxiety, depression, trauma, dementia, and end-of-life care, while continuing live and studio collaborations.
Beyond music, Lance is the founder of Elemental Health in St. George, specializing in hormone optimization, IV therapy, peptides, and medical weight loss. He is preparing to begin osteopathic medical school in 2026 in Ivins, Utah. A lifelong metalhead with eclectic tastes, Lance draws inspiration from genres spanning cinematic scores to bluegrass. When not composing, he’s outdoors hiking or searching for great Indian food—usually with a harp or cello close by.

# **The State Street Circuit**

There’s a line that runs straight down the valley, louder than traffic and older than most of the buildings around it.

From North Temple to the south end of the valley, these are the bars on State Street, or within one block east or west, that still put live music on a stage. Jazz rooms, punk dives, biker bars, piano joints, metal rooms, blues corners, and **Ice Haus**, sitting right where it belongs.

No clubs three neighborhoods away.

No “close enough” stretches.

Just the actual corridor.

We mapped it like a Where’s Waldo page because half the fun is noticing what’s been there the whole time.

This is **The State Street Circuit**.
If you’ve played it, you know.
If we missed a stop, call it out.

Music only works when people show up.

# **TRS 2026 - **

Welcome @everyone. 

We want to clarify how we operate as a team.

This week, we removed a member from our community after **repeated violations** of our conduct standards. That decision wasn’t about taste, reach, or disagreement. It was about **behavior**.

We *actively* invite people to volunteer for airspace on our stream schedule. The door is open to DJs, selectors, musicians, and hosts who want to contribute time, ideas, and energy to something community-driven. We believe in giving people a platform.

That openness, however, comes with a baseline expectation: mutual respect. Personal attacks, harassment, or intimidation toward anyone involved are not tolerated.

When boundaries are crossed, access is removed. We don’t argue publicly. We don’t escalate. We move on. In this case, we’re grateful the issue surfaced early and before more time or energy was invested.

Our focus remains the same: documenting real moments, supporting independent music, and building something that lasts.

If you’re here for the music and the community, you’re welcome.
If not, this isn’t the place.

Back to work.

UTAH ARTIST TOP 10 CHALLENGE 
Alright Rock Salt crew, time to stir the local pot. We want your personal Top 10 songs by Utah artists—past, present, famous, or not. 

Maybe it’s that band that only played one show at Kilby in 2012. Maybe it’s your cousin’s prog-folk duo that never made it out of Spanish Fork. Doesn’t matter. If it’s got Utah energy, it counts.

Example Entry:

 “Top 10 from Some Guy I Met at the Maverik in Nephi”

1. “Snow Tires and Heartbreaks” – The Freeway Ghosts

2. “Jell-O and Gasoline” – Elder Spleen

3. “Provo Glow” – Sister Missionary Position

4. “Don’t Text Me, I’m at Lagoon” – The Thrill Seekers

5. “Utah County Gothic” – Tithing Refund

6. “Seagull of Love” – Brigham and the Bears

7. “I Left My Heart in a Dutch Oven” – Zion’s Fist

8. “Kearns After Midnight” – The Black Tops

9. “Bishop’s Daughter” – Neon Draper

10. “I-15 Blues (Exit 260 Remix)” – Diesel Dan & the Merge Lanes

Now your turn. Drop your own Utah Top 10 in the comments. Doesn’t matter if it’s real, semi-real, or pure myth. Let’s see who remembers the basement shows, the coffee shops, and the bands that should’ve blown up but didn’t.

 We’ll talk the “People’s Playlist” next week!
